land, United Kingdom","Eaglesham, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Eaglesham, Renfrewshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"FitzWalter","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English, Irish: relationship name from Anglo-Norman French  <i>fiz</i> ‘son’ (  see  Fitz  ) + the personal name   Walter  , ‘son of  <i>Walter</i>’."],"variants":[{"name":"Fitzwater","meanings":["Irish: altered form of <b>Fitzwalter</b>, a patronymic from Anglo-Norman French <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son’ (see   Fitz  ) + the personal name   Walter  , meaning ‘son of <i>Walter</i>’.","History: This is the name of a family of Norman origin, descended from Godfrey, Count of Brionne (died <i>c.</i> 1010). Godfrey's grandson, Richard FitzGilbert, accompanied William the Conqueror and was made Lord of Clare. His great-grandson was Robert FitzWalter, one of the barons who guaranteed the Magna Carta in 1215."]},{"name":"Walter","meanings":["English (of Norman origin), German, Dutch, Polish, Swedish, and Danish: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This personal name was introduced into England both in the reign of Edward the Confessor and by the Normans (in the forms <i>Walt(i)er</i>, <i>Waut(i)er</i>). After the Norman Conquest it soon became one of the most popular personal names in Britain. Compare   Walther  .","Germanized or Americanized form of Czech, Slovak, Croatian, and Slovenian <b>Valter</b> and Czech <b>Valtr</b>: from the personal name <i>Valter</i>, <i>Valtr</i>, of ancient Germanic origin (see 1 above)."]},{"name":"Fitz","meanings":["English: from Anglo-Norman French <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son’ (from Latin <i>filius</i>), used originally to distinguish a son from a father bearing the same personal name and then conventionalized as a hereditary surname, or short for a surname of which <i>fiz</i> ‘son’ was the first element, for example   Fitzhenry   and   Fitzroy  .","Altered form of English   Fitch  .","German: from a vernacular pet form of the personal name <i>Vinzenz</i> (see   Vincent  ) or <i>Vitus</i> (see   Vito  , compare   Veit  ). Compare also   Fietz  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]},{"name":"Marjory","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual modern spelling of   Margery .  It seems to have arisen as the result of folk etymological association of the name with that of the herb <i>marjoram</i> (  compare  Rosemary  ). This word is of uncertain origin; its Middle English and Old French form was <i>majorane</i>, without the first <i>-r-</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Marjory FitzWalter was born in 1127, in Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland, United Kingdom. She had at least 2 sons with Robert de Montgomery."},"et":{"1127–":"1127–Surnud","1125–1165":"1125–1165","1144–1221":"1144–1221","–Male":"Surnud","1127–Female":"1127–Surnud","1127":"1127","1125":"1125","1221":"1221","1144":"1144","1165":"1165","about 1144":"umbes 1144","1180":"1180","Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Paisley, Renfrewshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Eaglesham, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Eaglesham, Renfrewshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"1127–":"1127–Kuollut","1125–1165":"1125–1165","1144–1221":"1144–1221","–Male":"Kuollut","1127–Female":"1127–Kuollut","1127":"1127","1125":"1125","1221":"1221","1144":"1144","1165":"1165","about 1144":"noin 1144","1180":"1180","Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Paisley, Renfrewshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Eaglesham, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Eaglesham, Renfrewshire, Scotland"},"fr":{"1127–":"1127–Décédée","1125–1165":"1125–1165","1144–1221":"1144–1221","–Male":"Décédé","1127–Female":"1127–Décédée","1127":"1127","1125":"1125","1221":"1221","1144":"1144","1165":"1165","about 1144":"environ 1144","1180":"1180","Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Paisley, Renfrewshire, Écosse, Royaume-Uni","Eaglesham, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Eaglesham, Renfrewshire, Écosse","lifeSummary":"Margaret Marjory FitzWalter est née en 1127, à Paisley, Renfrewshire, Écosse, Royaume-Uni. Elle a eu au moins 2 fils avec Robert de Montgomery."},"de":{"1127–":"1127–Verstorben","1125–1165":"1125–1165","1144–1221":"1144–1221","–Male":"Verstorben","1127–Female":"1127–Verstorben","1127":"1127","1125":"1125","1221":"1221","1144":"1144","1165":"1165","about 1144":"um 1144","1180":"1180","Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Paisley, Renfrewshire, Schottland, United Kingdom","Eaglesham, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Eaglesham, Renfrewshire, Scotland","lifeSummary":"Margaret Marjory FitzWalter wurde 1127 in 